{"id": "785263", "revid": "14511", "url": "https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=785263", "title": "Wheelchair Rugby Tri-Nations Series begins in Sydney", "text": "Cathedral Square, Sydney, Australia \u2014\n\"Wikinews\" attended the Wheelchair Rugby Tri-Nations Series in Cathedral Square, Sydney, ongoing from Wednesday. This is the first time an international wheelchair rugby event has been held outdoors, and in this arena. Three nations are competing: the United States, Australia, and New Zealand.\nThe venue is Cathedral Square, Sydney, which is adjacent to . The Sydney Central Business district is on the other side of the park. An outdoor stadium has been constructed specifically for the tournament, which is believed to be the first time an international wheelchair rugby tournament has been held outdoors. This choice was validated by the fine and warm weather. Free sunscreen was given to the crowd.\nThe Opening Ceremony was officiated by Australian Paralympic Committee Chief Executive Officer . In attendance were the Premier of , , the Deputy Lord Mayor of Sydney, Robyn Kemmis, and Paralympic swimmer . A large crowd, mostly consisting of school groups, was entertained by boy band singing their hit \"\". \nEach team is to play the others two twice, on Wednesday September 18 and Thursday September 19. Finals are to be held on Friday. \nAll three teams are highly ranked internationally. The United States team is ranked number one in the world. It won bronze at the in , gold at the in , and bronze at the in , and is the current world champion. This is its first visit to Australia since the . \nThe , known as the Steelers, is ranked second in the world. It won silver in Beijing and gold in London. The team is almost unchanged from the one that won in London. has become the assistant coach.\nThe first game, held immediately after the Opening Ceremony, was between the United States and Australia. The United States proved the better team, forcing errors and turnovers. Three turnovers in the first quarter were especially costly for the Steelers, who lost 56\u201343.\nThe second game was held at 17:30 under lights. The crowd was small, but there were a number of New Zealand fans in the crowd, including a few . Two of the New Zealand players are also Maori. The well-disciplined United States team proved too good for the Wheel Blacks as well, who lost 58\u201340 in an entertaining contest.\nThe third game was at 19:30, between Australia and New Zealand. The Australians led the whole game, which was nonetheless entertaining to the last. In the dying seconds of the game, Australia's shunted a stalling New Zealand player across the line to force him to score, then threw the ball to team mate , who raced for the line at high speed but was beaten by the buzzer. Australia won 61\u201348.\nThe New Zealand team, known as the Wheel Blacks, is ranked tenth in the world. It won gold in Athens.\nHighlights of the tournament are scheduled to be shown on Sports in Australia on September 28 and 29. \nSources.\n "}
