 recreational hunting in national parks, as it was announced in May 2012 by New South Wales Premier . This amendment of the Game and Feral Animal Control Act was part of a deal with the . The government needed at least one vote from a Shooters and Fishers Party MP to pass electricity privatisation legislation, as both and Greens opposed it. O'Farrell's plans to allow pest control by licensed individuals called for licencing by the of New South Wales.\nFollowing a report sharply criticizing the Game Council, the government dissolved it in mid-2013, suspended hunting on public lands, and reconsidered the plan to allow amateur hunters into national parks \u2014 thus breaking the earlier promise to the Shooters and Fishers Party."}
