ved a stop-and-go penalty and finished outside the points. \nStewards had further punishment for the Lotus driver after the race. He will have a five-place grid position penalty at the start of his race in China. He also had three points added to his racing driver's licence, a new system this year comparable to a normal motorist receiving points after traffic offences.\nMaldonado seemed to imply the other driver played a roll in the collision. \"We will need to have a look again at what happened,\" he said, \"as Esteban seemed to be off his line coming into turn one \u2014 maybe he missed his braking point, I don't know \u2014 and by then I was in the corner with nowhere to go\". \nFan opinion is sharply against him, with some using the derogatory nickname Crashtor Maldonado. Others said his punishment was unfair compared to Ricciardo's ten-place grid position drop after his team's mistake in Malaysia. Guti\u00e9rrez thanked supportive fans via social media after the race in English and Mexican, and returned to the circuit yesterday as teams took to testing. \nMaldonado was not alone in causing accidents. received a drive-through penalty after colliding with , leaving both cars sporting punctures. Sutil later retired from the race.\nOther retirements included and , both rookies, who separately pulled up at the trackside. Fellow newcomer of Russia, who claimed the title of F1's youngest-ever points scorer at the season opener, was placed just outside the points despite setting one of the fastest laps of the early part of the race. He had also scored in Malaysia.\n\"Not an easy race for us yesterday!\" Kvyat tweeted on Monday. \"But many things learned, and helpful for the future.\"\nThe podium was rounded out by in third, claiming 's second-ever podium finish off the back of a failure to even start in Malaysia with a gearbox malfunction. took fifth. Both he and ninth-place celebrated upon completing the race, arms in the air. racers and scored seventh and eight place respectively. claimed the final scoring position of tenth despite a minor collision with Magnussen at the race start.\nWilliams, who this year are using new bright white livery on their cars, where able to keep the coloured stripes of sponsor . Constraints from the host nation meant the word Martini itself, however, was changed to 'racing' on the cars. Williams test driver of Scotland started a competition during the race weekend to win one of her Martini-coloured caps for submitting pictures of designs using the Martini colours.\nA further near miss was suffered by Bottas when he ran off-track after becoming caught in battling between R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Ricciardo. His team radioed to promise a complaint would be made to race director .\nRosberg told his Twitter followers \"Great fight with @LewisHamilton but I'm back in two weeks to take the win\". Hamilton tweeted \"What a race! Amazing to get my first win in Bahrain\" and also paid tribute to his Mercedes team.\nAnti-government protestors turned out in their thousands at the start of the race weekend. The peaceful rally at the capital, , was marred by small groups throwing at police. The protestors were opposed to the international attraction giving patronage to Bahrain. Events at the circuit were given heavy security.\nThe race has been the target of intense protesting for several years. "}
